                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d475">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3537: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName> [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1920-10-12T10:33:00-04:00"
                            notBefore="1920-10-10T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>].<lb/>[Received October 12, 1920—10:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>314. Following from Canton October 10, 4 p.m.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>Referring to my telegram of October 4, 5 p.m.<note n="47" xml:id="d475fn47"
                            >Not printed.</note> Tang Ting Kwang was installed at Honam Friday by
                        his partisans as military governor. Mo remains master of the situation and
                        refuses to resign his position, grows stronger daily, probability of
                        fighting less imminent. British Legation requested to arrange peace between
                        North and South. Kindly inform the Department. Bergholz.</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
